/*-----------------------------------------
LeetCode 567 - Permutation in String
Pattern:Fixed Sliding Window + Hashing

Approach:
1. If s1 is longer than s2, return false.
2. Store the frequency of characters in s1.
3. Create another frequency array for the first window of s2 having size equal to s1.
4. Compare both frequency arrays.
5. Slide the window:
   - Add the new character entering the window.
   - Remove the leftmost character leaving the window.
6. After each slide, compare the two frequency arrays.
7. If they match, a permutation exists.

Time Complexity:O(n)
Space Complexity:O(1)

Reason:
- Two frequency arrays of size 26 are used.
- 26 is constant because only lowercase English letters are allowed.

Key Learning:
- Fixed-size Sliding Window is used when the required window length is known.
- Frequency arrays are faster than unordered_map for lowercase English letters.
- Only two characters change when the window slides.

Mistakes I Made:  Initially tried counting the frequency of the entire s2 instead of the current window.
-----------------------------------------
*/

class Solution {
public:
    bool checkInclusion(string s1, string s2) {
        vector<int>freq1(26,0);
        vector<int>freq2(26,0);
        if(s1.size()>s2.size()) return false;
        for(int i=0;i<s1.size();i++)
        {
            freq1[s1[i]-'a']++;
        }
        int k=s1.size();
        for(int i=0;i<k;i++)
        {
            freq2[s2[i]-'a']++;
        }
        if(freq1==freq2) return true;
        for(int i=k;i<s2.size();i++)
        {
            freq2[s2[i]-'a']++;
            freq2[s2[i-k]-'a']--;
            if(freq1==freq2) return true;
        }
        return false;

    }
};
